<p>The post <a href="https://techwireasia.com/2026/04/southeast-asia-leads-the-world-in-ai-optimism-its-governance-frameworks-are-nowhere-near-ready/">Southeast Asia leads the world in AI optimism. Its governance frameworks are nowhere near ready.</a> appeared first on <a href="https://techwireasia.com">TechWire Asia</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<ul>
<li><strong>Southeast Asia leads the world in AI optimism, but governance frameworks haven&#8217;t caught up.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Malaysia posted the largest AI optimism increase, although responsible AI maturity hasn&#8217;t kept pace.</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Southeast Asia trusts AI more than anywhere else in the world. Stanford University&#8217;s <a href="https://hai.stanford.edu/ai-index/2026-ai-index-report">2026 AI Index Report</a>, published this week, documents exactly how the gap between that optimism and its governance infrastructure has become.</p>
<p>In Malaysia, Thailand, Indonesia, and Singapore, more than 80% of respondents say AI will profoundly change their lives in the next three to five years. Malaysia recorded the largest increase of any country surveyed from 2024 to 2025, up nine percentage points on that measure.</p>
<p>North American and European respondents sit at the opposite end – lower excitement, higher nervousness. The US ranks 24th in generative AI adoption at 28.3%, while Singapore is at 61% and the UAE is at 54%.</p>
<figure id="attachment_247278" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-247278" style="width: 1102px" class="wp-caption aligncentre"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-247278 size-full" src="https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.49.20-PM.png" alt="" width="1102" height="534" srcset="https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.49.20-PM.png 1102w, https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.49.20-PM-300x145.png 300w, https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.49.20-PM-1024x496.png 1024w, https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.49.20-PM-768x372.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1102px) 100vw, 1102px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-247278" class="wp-caption-text"><em>Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, and China cluster in the high-excitement, low-nervousness quadrant – visibly separated from North American and European markets. Source: Ipsos AI Monitor 2025, via Stanford HAI 2026 AI Index Report</em></figcaption></figure>
<p>The issue is what sits on the other side of that optimism.</p>
<h3>High AI optimism, uneven governance</h3>
<p>The Stanford report&#8217;s responsible AI chapter draws on a survey conducted jointly with McKinsey in multiple regions and industries. In 2025, the global average responsible AI maturity score was 2.3 on a four-point scale, meaning most organisations are still integrating responsible AI practices not having them fully operational.</p>
<p>Asia-Pacific registered 2.5, the highest regional score, but that still places the region firmly in the &#8220;integrating&#8221; band not anything approaching comprehensive operational control. The maturity scale captures whether organisations have responsible AI policies embedded into how decisions get made.</p>
<p>At 2.5, the region is ahead of North America at 2.2 and Latin America at 2.2 – but the gap between a score of 2.5 and the full operational standard of 4.0 is substantial. Knowledge and training gaps were the top obstacle to responsible AI implementation globally in 2025, cited by 59% of respondents – up from 51% in 2024. For a region where public AI enthusiasm is outpacing enterprise governance infrastructure, that skills gap is the most immediate vulnerability.</p>
<h3>The trust picture and what it reveals</h3>
<figure id="attachment_247277" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-247277" style="width: 300px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-247277 size-medium" src="https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.48.14-PM-300x283.png" alt="" width="300" height="283" srcset="https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.48.14-PM-300x283.png 300w, https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.48.14-PM-768x725.png 768w, https://techwireasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Screenshot-2026-04-15-at-4.48.14-PM.png 925w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-247277" class="wp-caption-text"><em>Southeast Asian countries rank among the world&#8217;s most trusting of their governments to regulate AI, with Singapore leading all 30 surveyed countries at 81%. The US sits last at 31%. Source: Ipsos AI Monitor 2025, via Stanford HAI 2026 AI Index Report</em></figcaption></figure>
<p>Southeast Asian countries report high trust in their governments to regulate AI. Singapore leads all 30 surveyed countries at 81%, followed by Indonesia at 76%, Malaysia at 73%, and Thailand at 70%. The global average is 54%. The US sits last at 31%.</p>
<p>That trust advantage is because government credibility creates the conditions for meaningful AI governance to be implemented and accepted. Countries where the public distrusts their government&#8217;s ability to regulate AI face a harder path to building the oversight infrastructure that responsible deployment requires.</p>
<p>But trust in government and the existence of adequate governance frameworks are not the same thing. The Stanford report notes that national AI strategies are expanding, particularly among developing economies, and that state-backed investments in AI supercomputing are rising. Yet model production remains concentrated in the US and China.</p>
<p>Southeast Asian countries are largely consumers and deployers of AI systems built elsewhere – which means the governance frameworks they develop need to account for dependency on foreign AI infrastructure, not domestic deployment.</p>
<h3>Where the optimism-governance tension is sharpest</h3>
<p>In India, China, Nigeria, the UAE, and Saudi Arabia, over 80% of employees reported using AI at work on a semi-regular or regular basis. For India specifically – which posted the sharpest rise in AI nervousness of any country surveyed, up 14 percentage points with a modest two-point increase in excitement – the picture is a region where use is accelerating faster than comfort.</p>
<p>Organisational support for responsible AI governance also shows a regional pattern worth noting. According to the University of Melbourne and KPMG global workplace survey cited in the report, India scored among the highest for organisational support of AI strategy and governance, with around 85 to 90% of respondents saying their organisation supports all three.</p>
<p>Countries at the other end of the scale – Japan and South Korea among them – reported the lowest levels of support for AI literacy and the least confidence in responsible AI governance. That split shows the highest workplace AI use and organisational commitment to governance is also the one experiencing the fastest-rising anxiety. High adoption and great concern are running simultaneously, which is precisely the condition that tends to produceregulatory action.</p>
<h3>Malaysia&#8217;s position</h3>
<p>Malaysia&#8217;s nine-point jump in AI optimism is the largest of any country in the Ipsos survey, and it arrives in a context the report doesn&#8217;t cover, but <em>Tech Wire Asia</em> readers will recognise. The country is the fastest-growing digital economy in Southeast Asia, holds around half of all planned regional data centre capacity, and has a prime minister who has committed RM2 billion to a sovereign AI cloud.</p>
<p>There is no national mandate for <a href="https://techwireasia.com/2026/04/ai-literacy-national-education-workforce/">AI in school curricula</a> – a gap covered separately in the Stanford report&#8217;s education chapter, which finds over 80% of Malaysian respondents expecting AI to profoundly change their lives, against a policy environment that has not formalised AI literacy at the school level.</p>
<p>Public enthusiasm outpacing policy infrastructure is not unusual in fast-moving markets. What makes Malaysia&#8217;s position distinctive is the scale of the infrastructure investment arriving with that enthusiasm. The governance question – who oversees AI systems operating on Malaysian data, in Malaysian data centres, under Malaysian regulatory frameworks that are still being shaped – will not wait for the enthusiasm to mature into policy.</p>
<h3>What the numbers say</h3>
<p>Stanford&#8217;s report documents where sentiment and governance infrastructure each stand and lets the gaps speak for themselves. What those gaps say is that a region with some of the world&#8217;s strongest AI confidence scores is building its governance capacity from a position of genuine institutional trust, which is an advantage, but on a compressed timeline, against systems and models it largely did not build, in a global regulatory environment where the EU is trusted more than any single national government to set the standards.</p>
